  "provider_reasoning_summaries": [
    "Let me analyze the mapped transformation to identify the reaction center.\n\nLooking at the reaction SMIRKS:\n[H:10][B-:11](CC)(CC)CC.[Li+].C1CCC[CH:20](CCC1)[Br:21] >> [H:10][CH:20]1CCCCCCC1.[Li+].[B:11](CC)(CC)CC.[Br-:21]\n\nLet me trace the atom mappings:\n\nReactants:\n- [H:10] is attached to [B-:11] in LiBHEt3 (triethylborohydride, lithium salt)\n- [B-:11] has three ethyl groups (CC)(CC)CC and one H\n- [Li+] is the counterion\n- [CH:20] is part of a cyclohexyl ring (C1CCC[CH:20](CCC1)) and is attached to [Br:21]\n\nProducts:\n- [H:10] is now attached to [CH:20] forming cyclohexane: [H:10][CH:20]1CCCCCCC1\n- [Li+] remains\n- [B:11] now has three ethyl groups only: [B:11](CC)(CC)CC (no H attached)\n- [Br-:21] is now a bromide ion\n\nSo the reaction center involves:\n1. Bond broken: B-H (between B:11 and H:10) - the hydride leaves boron\n2. Bond broken: C-Br (between CH:20 and Br:21) - bromine leaves the carbon\n3. Bond formed: C-H (between CH:20 and H:10) - hydride adds to carbon\n\nThis is a nucleophilic substitution where the borohydride (B-H) acts as a nucleophile, the C-Br bond breaks, and a new C-H bond forms. The boron loses its hydride and becomes neutral triethylborane.\n\nThe reaction center is:\n- Bonds broken: B:11-H:10, C:20-Br:21\n- Bonds formed: C:20-H:10\n\nThis is essentially a hydride transfer from boron to carbon, with bromide leaving."
